In the late 1920s, Disney moved to New York City to work on a series of animated films for Universal Pictures. He returned to Hollywood in the mid-1930s and founded the Walt Disney Studio. In the late 1950s, Disney expanded into television with The Mickey Mouse Club and Disneyland, a live-action/animated series that aired on ABC from 1954–1967.

In the late 1960s, Disney began working on plans for a theme park called Disneyland Resort, which opened in Anaheim, California, in July 1955. Disneyland Resort has since expanded into three theme parks: Disneyland Park, Disney California Adventure Park, and Walt Disney World Resort in Orlando, Florida.
